version: 1
display_name: VCFR-9X-000028 - The router must not be configured to have any feature enabled that calls home to the vendor.
global_description: |-
  Call home services will routinely send data such as configuration and diagnostic information to the vendor for routine or emergency analysis and troubleshooting. There is a risk that transmission of sensitive data sent to unauthorized persons could result in data loss or downtime due to an attack.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFR-9X-000028
  srg:
    - SRG-NET-000131-RTR-000083
  cci:
    - CCI-002403
  nist:
    - SC-7 (11)
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_nsx_routing:
    type: custom
    desc: The router must not be configured to have any feature enabled that calls home to the vendor.
    control_id: VCFR-9X-000028
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From the NSX Manager web interface, go to System >> Settings >> General Settings >> Customer Program.

      Next to Customer Experience Improvement Program, select "Edit".

      If "Join the VMware Customer Experience Improvement Program" is checked, this is a finding.

      If Schedule is enabled, this is finding.
    rationale: |-
      Call home services will routinely send data such as configuration and diagnostic information to the vendor for routine or emergency analysis and troubleshooting. There is a risk that transmission of sensitive data sent to unauthorized persons could result in data loss or downtime due to an attack.
    remediation: |-
      From the NSX Manager web interface, go to System >> Settings >> General Settings >> Customer Program.

      Next to Customer Experience Improvement Program, select "Edit".

      Uncheck "Join the VMware Customer Experience Improvement Program", set "Schedule" to disabled, and then click "Save".
